<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-03-02T22:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-03-02T22:36:00-05:00" n="902" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d902">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/6449.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-03-02T21:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 2, 1913—9 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>69. I am informed by the National Railways officials that armed bodies of
                            men continue to cut the railways at various points and burn bridges,
                            especially between San Luis Potosí and Monterey, where Carranza, though
                            formally submitted to the Government, is in arms. The Government informs
                            me that they are gradually surrounding him and will suppress the
                            movement quickly.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
